{"cursor":"10898","size":15,"audio":[],"cat":[],"tmpl":[],"currentlang":"en","linknr":252,"url":"Rod_cells","article":"__NOTOC__ {{Infobox neuron |neuron_name = Rod cell |image_neuron = Fig\nretine.png |caption_neuron = Cross section of the retina. Rods are visible at\nfar right. |location = Retina |function = Low light photoreceptor\n|neurotranmitter = Glutamate |morphology = rod shaped |afferents = None\n|efferents = Bipolar Cells and Horizontal cells |NeuroLex = Rod Cell |NeuroLexID\n= sao1458938856 |Code = | }} 'Rod cells', or 'rods', are photoreceptor cells in\nthe retina of the eye that can function in less intense light than can the other\ntype of visual photoreceptor, cone cells. Rods are concentrated at the outer\nedges of the retina and are used in peripheral vision. On average, there are\napproximately 125 million rod cells in the human retina. Curcio, C. A., K.\nR. Sloan, et al. (1990). \"Human photoreceptor topography.\" The Journal of\nComparative Neurology 292(4): 497-523. More sensitive than cone cells, rod\ncells are almost entirely responsible for night vision.\n","recorded":1362123917,"portal":[],"list":[],"links":"253","instances":["anatomy","anatomy","biology","medycyna","anatomical","biology","cell","biologi","oko","oko","synet","penglihatan","human_eye","auge"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Human eye anatomy","Histology","Photoreceptor cells","Human cells","Neurons"],"headings":["Structure and function","Sensitivity","Response to light","See also","References","External links"],"tags":[["nucleus","cell"],["hyperpolarization","biology"],["morphology","biology"],["nucleus","cell"],["hyperpolarization","biology"],["globe","human_eye"],["iris","anatomy"],["iris","anatomy"],["optic_cup","anatomical"],["lens","anatomy"],["http://ca.wikipedia.org/wiki/bast%c3%b3","c%c3%a8l%c2%b7lula"],["http://cs.wikipedia.org/wiki/ty%c4%8dinka","oko"],["http://da.wikipedia.org/wiki/stav","synet"],["http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/st%c3%a4bchen","auge"],["http://es.wikipedia.